answers.body_markdown:
All you need is the built-in [`Object.values()`][1]:

&gt; `Object.values()` returns an array whose elements are the enumerable property values found on the object. 


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const map = {&quot;hi&quot;:[&quot;hello&quot;,&quot;hey&quot;,&quot;howdy&quot;],&quot;bye&quot;:[&quot;Goodbye&quot;,&quot;Ciao&quot;]};
    const output = Object.values(map);

    console.log(output);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/values

Using reduce the return pushs to &#39;output&#39; no need to push yourself:

      return Object.keys(map).reduce((output, key) =&gt; {
          return map[key]
      },[])

You could also use map:

      return Object.keys(map).map((key) =&gt; {
          return map[key]
      })

Apart from the above two excellent answers, you may choose to use [Object.entries()][1], which will return an array from the input object&#39;s `[key, value]` pair. From there, we can return only the `value` into the resulting array, giving you the expected result.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const input = {&quot;hi&quot;:[&quot;hello&quot;,&quot;hey&quot;,&quot;howdy&quot;],&quot;bye&quot;:[&quot;Goodbye&quot;,&quot;Ciao&quot;]}
    const result = Object.entries(input).map(item =&gt; item[1]);

    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

However, do take note that `Object.entries()` is not supported by Internet Explorer browsers.

Alternatively, you may use the good old [for..in][2] statement to iterate through the enumerable properties of the object, followed by pushing the corresponding values to the resulting array. 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const input = {&quot;hi&quot;:[&quot;hello&quot;,&quot;hey&quot;,&quot;howdy&quot;],&quot;bye&quot;:[&quot;Goodbye&quot;,&quot;Ciao&quot;]}

    const result = []
    for (const property in input) {
      result.push(input[property]);
    }

    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/entries
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/for...in

